278,112,1,0,0,'Shakespeare\'s Language','9780140285925','','','',0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,'<p>Frank Kermode</p>\r\n<p>Shakespeare&rsquo;s plays are often in language that is difficult for us, and must have been hard even for contemporaries. How and why did Shakespeare\'s language develop as it did? Kermode argues that the resources of English underwent major change around 1600.</p>\r\n<p>Paperback</p>','jpg',0,6,0,2,0,'a:0:{}',0,'a:0:{}','',1,'N;',0,0,0,'','','',0,0,'','','2011-04-16 15:52:18','2011-04-16 16:25:49',3
279,113,1,0,0,'The Shakespeare Miscelleny','9780140515558','','','',0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,'<div>David Crystal &amp; Ben Crystal</div>\r\n<div>An illuminating and endlessly absorbing treasury of observations about the world &amp; work of Shakespeare.&nbsp; Bring together a host of little-known facts and intriguing insights into the plays and poems, as well as essential information about the man behind them and the dynamic Elizabethan theatrical world in which he worked.</div>\r\n<div>Hardback</div>','jpg',0,0,0,0,0,'a:0:{}',0,'a:0:{}','',1,'N;',0,0,0,'','','',0,0,'','','2011-04-16 15:59:04','2011-04-16 15:59:04',1
280,22,1,0,0,'Shakespeare & Co','9780141017136','','','',8.99,0,0,0,320,0,0,0,0,'<p>Stanley Wells</p>\r\n<p>An accessible introduction to the brilliant Elizabethan and Jacobian playwrights who were contempories of Shakespeare: Christopher Marlowe, Thomas Dekker, Ben Jonson, Thomas Middleton, John Fletcher, Francis Beaumont and John Webster.</p>\r\n<p>Chapters cover the theatrical scene and a brief look at some of the best known actors of the day.</p>\r\n<p>Paperback<br /><br /></p>','jpg',0,10,0,2,0,'a:0:{}',0,'a:0:{}','',1,'N;',0,0,0,'','','',0,1,'','','2011-04-16 16:57:02','2011-04-18 11:35:41',5
281,22,1,0,0,'The Lodger','9780141023748','','','',8.99,0,0,0,460,0,0,0,0,'<p>Charles Nicholl</p>\r\n<p>In 1612 Shakespeare gave evidence at the Court of Requests in Westminster - it is the only occasion his spoken words are recorded. The case was routine but it opens up an unexpected window into the dramatist\'s famously obscure life-story.</p>\r\n<p>Charles Nicholl applies a powerful biographical magnifying glass to this fascinating episode in Shakespeare\'s life. He conjures up a detailed and compelling description of the circumstances in which Shakespeare lived and worked, and in which he wrote such plays as \"Othello\", \"Measure for Measure\", and \"King Lear\".</p>\r\n<p>Paperback</p>','jpg',0,10,0,2,0,'a:0:{}',0,'a:0:{}','',1,'N;',0,0,0,'','','',0,1,'','','2011-04-16 16:58:56','2011-04-18 11:38:11',6
